  "name": "Canvas + Dependency Expansion + Export Pipeline",
  "createdAt": "2026-03-16T20:00:00.000Z",
  "intent": "Understand the core feature of the Visual Context Node Builder: how files are added to the canvas, how dependencies are expanded and filtered, how nodes are rendered and managed in state, and how the full context is built and exported as Markdown/XML. This covers the complete data flow from extension host (file reading, AST scanning, dependency resolution) through the message protocol to the React webview (canvas rendering, state management, export formatting).",
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "sys-1",
      "type": "systemInstruction",
      "position": { "x": 0, "y": 0 },
      "data": {
        "text": "You are analyzing the core pipeline of a VS Code extension that builds visual context for AI. The pipeline has 3 layers:\n\n1. EXTENSION HOST — reads files, scans imports, resolves dependencies, extracts symbols\n2. MESSAGE PROTOCOL — typed postMessage bridge between extension and webview\n3. REACT WEBVIEW — React Flow canvas, Zustand stores, node components, export formatters\n\nFocus on data flow: how a file goes from disk → extension host → message → webview store → canvas node → export bundle."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "note-architecture",
      "type": "stickyNote",
      "position": { "x": 0, "y": 250 },
      "data": {
        "text": "ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW\n\nThe pipeline flows left-to-right:\n\n1. Extension host reads files and scans AST (import-scanner, symbol-extractor, dependency-graph)\n2. Results are sent via postMessage (messages.ts defines the protocol)\n3. useMessageHandler receives data and populates canvas-store\n4. Canvas.tsx renders React Flow with custom node components\n5. Toolbar triggers export via context-builder → format-markdown/format-xml\n\nKey gotcha: the webview runs in a sandboxed iframe — ALL file system access goes through the extension host via messages."
      }
    },
